Violin Memory's (VMEM) CEO Kevin DeNuccio on Q2 2017 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Violin Memory's (VMEM) CEO Kevin DeNuccio on Q2 2017 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptSep. 8.16 | About: Violin Memory, (VMEM) Violin Memory, Inc. (NYSE:VMEM)
Q2 2017 Earnings Conference Call
September 08, 2016, 05:00 PM ET
Executives
Cory Sindelar - CFO
Kevin DeNuccio - President and CEO
Analysts
Nehal Chokshi - Maxim Group
Operator
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you for standing by. Welcome to the Violin Memory Second Quarter Fiscal Year 2017 Financial Results Conference Call. [Operator Instructions]
I would now like to turn the conference over to Cory Sindelar, Violin Memory's Chief Financial Officer. Mr. Sindelar, please go ahead.
Cory Sindelar
Good afternoon and thank you for attending. Joining me today is Kevin DeNuccio, Violin Memory's President and Chief Executive Officer. Kevin will begin with his opening remarks on the quarter, and he will then say some words about Violin's outlook and strategy going forward. I will subsequently cover Violin's financial results.
During this call, we will reference both GAAP and non-GAAP financial measures. Our earnings release issued earlier today includes a reconciliation of GAAP to non-GAAP measures. The copy of this release is available on our website at www.violin-memory.com\investors. We will also make forward-looking statements within the meaning of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995, including projections and estimates and other forward-looking statements, regarding our future business and financial performance. We caution you that all forward-looking statements are based on management's current expectations or beliefs, and that our actual results may differ materially.
In addition to the risks and uncertainties that may be discussed during today's call, there are a number of other risks and uncertainties that may affect our future business and financial performance that are included in our quarterly report on Form 10-Q for the first quarter of fiscal year 2017, which was filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission, and is available on our Investor Relations page of our website, and on the SEC's website at www.sec.gov.
All forward-looking statements are based upon information available to the Company as of today, September 8, 2016, and we do not assume any obligation to update the forward-looking statements to reflect events that occur or circumstances that exist after today. Please keep this in mind when listening to a replay of this call.
I'll now turn the call over to Kevin for his opening remarks.
Kevin DeNuccio
Thanks, Cory. And good afternoon, everyone.
Revenues for the quarter were $7.5 million versus $9.7 million in prior quarter and $15.3 million a year ago. This quarter's performance is obviously frustrating and disappointing as we strongly believe it could be the quarter that returns revenue upward after a downward trend for more than a year. Both of our international theaters in the EMEA and APAC had extremely difficult product sales in the quarter. The international markets alone could account for a short fall from expectations.
For North America, we did see several customers expand their initial deployment of the FSP platform. However, the overall performance in the U.S. and for the company overall was primarily caused by our inability to close significant orders in time from our key Fortune 100 customers. Two of our top five customers have been testing or evaluating our new family of products, which were not available for revenue last quarter. We are on those products in a minute.
But this was a contributing factor in us not being able to generate product revenue with two of our top customers. Our target market of large Fortune 500 and Global 1000 companies makes orders naturally large and lumpy and challenging in terms of long sales cycles. And it's been a large part of our inability to consistently execute or return to growth. Bottom line is that it was a very tough quarter for us.

So, let me turn the conversation to what it means for the company going forward. We still believe Violin is on verge of reversing our revenue trend and heading upward. With this in mind we also believe several changes are necessary to accelerate the company's return to growth and enable long-term success. Most importantly Violin must retain our customer confidence in both our long-term plans and viability as a strategic technology provider.
I'd like to lay out the important pillars for our success going forward. First, is about Violin's technology leadership, disruptive innovation, and software maturity, which we believe can be the most important factors to renew revenue growth. We are on the verge of announcing a next generation family of Flash Storage Platform comprised of industry leading All Flash Arrays. The announcement is scheduled for next week on September 14, 2016.
We believe these new products will once again establish Violin as the leader in the combination of every category measured in AFAs; latency, affordability, density, scalability and performance. As it relates to eye-offs, Violin is doubling the performance of its current arrays while driving a five-fold improvement and consistent low latency while offering significant density and the lowest cost currently available.
We'll also announce the general availability of encryption software related to security that will make the Violin arrays the most secure storage arrays in the industry irrespective of whether data is in flight or at rest. This capability will be available on our legacy systems, as well as our new line of arrays.
We will also roll out of our vision and initial products around cloud storage, which will position the Violin's Flash Storage Platform as the best product line for building private, hybrid, and public clouds by leveraging Violin's newest market innovation for seamlessly integrating and communicating between these environments.
The offering of Concerto in the cloud will allow customers the ability to use any public cloud as a backup site disaster recovery or fail-over site or even use the cloud as a second or third tier of lower performance storage. All of these capabilities will be usable and accessible without any changes to any other public clouds, such as AWS, Azure or Google. 
And all managed from Violin's company management suite that enables a single pane of glass to be used to manage and organize customer data leveraging the Concerto operating system. We've achieved this by virtualizing Concerto, allowing it to run seamlessly and virtual machine in the cloud.
We feel the seamless private, public cloud integration is unique and strategic as large enterprises aggressively move to private, hybrid, and public cloud implementations. While enterprises have been migrating data and after the cloud over the last several years the coordination management and/or retrieval challenges of data have been very difficult. The Concerto in the cloud solution will address this customer pinpoint.
This announcement is a massive delivery of technology leadership and innovation and it demonstrates Violin's commitment to deliver technology leadership for its customers. This technology leadership is one of the key pillars for Violin's turnaround and a key tenant for the company's long-term successes.
As I just mentioned every two of our Fortune 100 customer order delays from last quarter were related to waiting for delivery of the new Flash Storage Platforms features and functionality. At the launch we will also discuss the company's vision for next generation technology such as NVMe over Fabrics.
I encourage you to go to our website to register to attend the September 14 product launch and vision webcast.
The second pillar of a long term viability and success as do with continuing to improve Violin's operational efficiencies overall cost structure and time to breakeven point. With our return to revenue growth taking much longer than we anticipated, we are attempting to build the most efficient organization possible to create longevity in our time to complete our turnaround.

Today we are announcing that we are broadening the responsibilities of Ebrahim Abbasi, our Chief Operating Officer. Ebrahim will assume sales and marketing responsibilities for the business in addition to his current responsibilities in R&D, customer support and manufacturing operations.
Said Ouissal, will be focused on transitioning sales and field operations responsibilities to Ebrahim and will assume his strategy position reporting directly to me. This is also part of reducing and taking a layer of management out of our senior ranks more appropriate to the size of the business.
Ebrahim has been key and leading the maturing and stabilizing actions of Violin’s product development, particularly to Concerto operating system over the last year, and he’s credited with leading a successful delivery of the new FSP products to be announced next week, while also driving Violin’s lower expense structure.
Ebrahim has always spent a lot of time in the field with customers and we believe his aggressive always upbeat positive attitude that is infectious, and have an impact we need to reinvigorating sales and customer confidence with the launch of the new products. And of course with my background of 25 years in sales, I will be intimately involved due to the critical importance of returning Violin to revenue growth.
In addition to the above actions, Violin also announced last quarter the opening of our first low cost R&D site in Kiev Ukraine in conjunction with our partner GlobalLogic. We've currently ramped to 20 developers with our intention to ramp to 50 by year end. This is a key element in our strategy to have the lowest cost structure in the industry without sacrificing our ability to keep our pace of innovation and technology leadership. Violin's remote R&D site will give the company the ability to scale at a significantly lower cost structure.
The third pillar to achieve success and viability for our customers and shareholders will be tightly managing both our cash on hand, and our ability to continue raising additional funding to address the company's projected losses through the profitability. This is where I'll be spending most of my immediate time.
In this regard, we finished last quarter with $36 million in cash after a $13 million cash burn in Q2. We believe our cost cutting and streamlining strategy will achieve a quarterly expense rate of under $11.5 million by Q1 over a 50% reduction from Q4 last year. This should reduce our quarterly burn to approximately $5 million at the beginning of the year from $13 million last quarter.
The impact of this will give us the lowest breakeven point of any of our public peers to between $70 million and $80 million in annual revenue. We believe that achieving this level of cash burn places us in the best position to obtain the necessary funding to continue to finance the business.
We are currently talking to both strategic and financial sponsors to address our need to raise capital and the overall financial structure of the company. We announced the filing of a shelf registration during last quarter for 20% of our outstanding shares.
Bruce Grant our largest shareholder and newest board member is leading this effort with me. Bruce continues to show his support and belief in the company. He will also continue to have open discussions with our bondholders in order to maximize the success and value creation of the business as we build towards profitability.
As I talk to customers and investors, I explain the difference and arbitrage between Wall Street evaluations of a company - in the Silicon Valley evaluation of a company. Wall Street primarily values financial metrics such as revenue growth, earnings or PEs, as well as cash user needs, the peer that we are paying the price for being public.

Where Silicon Valley values technology creation, differentiation, market opportunity and human talent, in this Silicon Valley regard, Violin remains an extremely valuable company with many of the best assets in an industry that is an enormous disruption and with incredible opportunity. And while it is very painful to navigate the Violin turnaround publicly, it gives our customers the ultimate transparency far above any private company or start-up or a comparison to our few public peers for using enormous burn rates to achieve their growth.
If it wasn't validated in this belief and what we offer to customers, one would have to believe that no startup could ever make it. I think one of the things the team and I underestimated with the difficulty and time needed in getting enterprise class maturity, reliability and customer confidence in a our comprehensive Concerto operating system.
Concerto operating is the broadest set of data services available in the industry in a native AFA operating system. It is Concerto that not only delivers always functionality but allows us to offer the first 69 Architecture in all-flash arrays. This architecture was formally only available in high-end legacy disk product such as EMC VMAX.
One other thing we spent - the last year focused is on hardening and maturing Concerto to deliver on the Flash Storage Platform 69 Architecture. And along with the launch of all the new FSP products, we will be delivering the latest release of Concerto version 7.6 that we have been hardening since last September.
As you know we are competing in a very different segment of the market in a public peers as we target the largest Global 1000 and Fortune 500 enterprises in almost critical application with this first last phase 69 Architecture. It’s been challenging for us because this Global 1000 business is big, lumpy and conservative around critical applications essential for their business.
However, as these mega franchises consisting of Fortune 500 and Global 1000 expand their Violin roll up to full production, we believe they will produce large ongoing revenue stream, that can serve as the foundation for the company’s growth and success.
Now I would also like to share some comments on the market and competition, as a competition is fierce. In 2016 the industry saw flash main streaming across the storage landscape, a position Violin staked out 18 months ago when the company first launched the Flash Storage Platform. We positioned our product and service capabilities along with our company mindset to enter into this largest segment in market opportunity.
We’ve seen a much change in competition over the last couple of quarters due to the mainstreaming of the market for flash. This is most notable with the biggest competitors in the business now reverting back to legacy architectures dust fully with SSDs and away from the acquired all-flash array platform. We believe this is primarily due to two factors. First, is the market need to go back to the full suite of features and functionality required in large enterprise primary storage market and applications.
This need consist of a completely integrated suite of features and reliability profile that is available in the FSP today. It's important to note that this tightly integrated offering is not available in any other startup or legacy competitor that offers in all-flash array.
The second factor is that raw flash cost curve level is defending fast enough that its becoming possible to meet competitive price point without e-duplication technology, which has been central for making flash affordable versus disk over the last couple of years.
We believe this cost reduction will further accelerate flash adoption in environments that are not well suited for e-duplication as they can simply migrate traditional second pin launch to flash to accelerate data base and high performance applications.

This is a segment where Violin first made its mark and had early success. Now with this broader market segment coming of age to flash and with Violin's continued innovation, Violin should once again be able to drive market adoption and success by serving the needs of these customers.
We still have many challenges to return to growth and complete our turnaround and with the pillars I laid out for our success above along with our structural changes, we are focused on our execution and the ability to be successful for our customers, investors and employees going forward.
Cory will now provide his remarks on our financial results.
Cory Sindelar
Thank you, Kevin.
Revenue for the first quarter was $7.5 million, a decrease of 23% sequentially from revenue of $9.7 million for the first quarter and a decrease of 51% from the year ago period, this result was below our guidance of $11 million to $13 million for the quarter.
Our total revenue 77% came from the Americas which is up from 70% last quarter. EMEA was 17% about the same as last quarter and Asia was down to 6% from 15% last quarter. We had two new customers down from seven in the prior quarter and new customers accounted for approximately 2% of our total revenue down from nearly 10% last quarter. And transactions direct with end user customers were about 34% of total revenue as compared with 28% last quarter.
Our GAAP gross margin for the second quarter was 3% as compared to 40% in the prior quarter. This was due to an inventory write-off, in light of our material reduction in sales - product sales relative to our forecast and the pending new product introduction we estimated that we have more inventory than needed to cover our forecasted sales for the current platform over the next 12 months. Based on this analysis we took an accounting charge of $2.9 million in the quarter. We still have the opportunity to sell these units in time like we have done with our 6000 Series products.
Our non-GAAP gross margin for the second quarter improved to 44% which compares to 42% last quarter and was below our guidance of 45% to 50%. The increase in gross margin versus prior quarter was due to the fact that service margin - our service revenue which is at higher gross margins was a larger percentage of total revenue.
Operating expenses on a GAAP basis were $19.1 million for the second quarter, which is down from $24.4 million for the first quarter.
Our non-GAAP operating expenses for the second quarter were lower by $2.3 million to $16.5 million as compared to $18.8 million in the first quarter, and were within our guidance of $16 million to $17 million. The decrease in expenses was the result of our restructuring that occurred in early March to align spending of revenue as we previously shared. We continue to restructure our operations to take expenses out.
As Kevin mentioned, we began an outsourcing project early in the second quarter, once fully implemented we expect this program will saves us $5 million annually. We expect the transition to be completed by the end of our fiscal year.
Total headcount at the end of the second quarter was 235, as compared to 258 at the end of the first quarter and to 318 at the end of last fiscal year. The decrease primarily relates to a reduction in our sales and marketing organization and to a lesser extent R&D.
Sales and marketing headcount at the end of the quarter was 78 versus 89 last quarter and engineering was 99 versus 108 last quarter. If you include the 20 plus developers we have on staff with GlobalLogic, our engineering workforce is greater than the prior quarter.
We ended the quarter with cash, cash equivalents and investments of $31.4 million and we had negative cash flows from operations of $13.5 million for the second quarter, which is on the low side of our guidance of $13 million to $15 million. For the six months ended July 31, 2016 we utilize $32.2 million of our cash to fund our operations.

Based on our current expectations for revenue in gross margin, we believe our existing cash balance is insufficient to operate the business for the next 12 months even as we continue to restructure our operations and reduce spending even further. As Kevin has mentioned, we are actively seeking additional cap further to fund our operations.
Since the end of the second quarter we have reduced our headcount by approximately 15%. We currently believe that our non-GAAP operating expenses for the third quarter will be between $15 million and $16 million.
We have decided not to provide quarterly guidance for at least the next two quarter as we are undergoing a lot of change including organizational changes and new product launch and reductions in our cost structure. Until we have better visibility we believe providing quarterly guidance will not be practical.
I will now turn the call back over to Kevin for his closing.
Kevin DeNuccio
Thanks, Cory.
We learned a lot over the last couple of years and we are taking these learnings including those from our mistakes and making the necessary adjustments. We strongly believe that the Flash Storage Platform including the new arrays we are unveiling on September 14, the maturity of the Concerto software and finally our new cloud strategy produce a successful outcome for our employees, customers and investors.
I will now turn the call over to Cory to begin the Q&A.
Cory Sindelar
Operator, please compile the queue for Q&A.
Question-and-Answer Session
Operator
[Operator Instructions] The first question comes from Nehal Chokshi with Maxim Group.
Nehal Chokshi
Yes. Hi, thanks. Shared a frustration by the way. Can you talk - I got personal questions as well, by the way. So let me know, so that I may get back into the queue. But first do you have an update on OEM partnership front?
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes. I mean, the biggest one that we have been working with - we are going to gauge in European theater primarily and couple of big opportunities in the U.S. But I think generally that relationship is not really done to the place where it's really producing any meaningful revenue and I'm not sure it's going in the next quarter or two either.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay. The breakeven model described 70 million, 80 million is your breakeven target and did I hear it correctly that the OpEx rate once the new rationalization of the OpEx structure will be $11 million per quarter, is that correct?
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes. Under 11.5, that's right.
Nehal Chokshi
Under 11.5, okay. So I back-out that that implies total gross margin profile of about 40% is that correct? And then I have follow-up based on that answer.
Kevin DeNuccio
No, I think that it's going to be - we think margins will be more in the 50% to 60% range probably at that time frame.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay.
Cory Sindelar
The interest as well.
Nehal Chokshi
I see. Okay.
Cory Sindelar
Operating expenses interest as well and I think that will get you to kind of what's the number…
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes, it’ll get you about the 5 million, yes.
Nehal Chokshi
Got it, okay. That's good. All right. So now regarding the new product that you're going to be - is it going to be released partly GA next week or you just introducing it next week?
Kevin DeNuccio
No, it's shipping starting next week GA, then in data.
Nehal Chokshi
Got it, okay. Now you described that part of the struggle was returning to the revenue ramp was proving that Concerto had a maturity that the large enterprises demand and there was hardening process associated with the Flash Storage Platforms?
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes.
Nehal Chokshi
Why shouldn’t there be that same hardening process that you went through on version one of FSP as what you'll be introducing what I'll recall version 2 next week?
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes, that's a good question. The hardening is really been around the operating system which we launched about 18 months ago. So it's been really the process of hardening the OS and not really the, OS’s interaction with the hardware. So that's where our challenges has been, so we really - we launched product about 18 months ago and 12 months ago like last September. We began a strategy of really hardening the software and quality that it's going to be delivered along with the new platforms next week.

So we really took the last year to do some extraordinary things in engineering and QA to get that product to where we think it needed to be for these critical applications that we are targeting in the largest companies. So it's really all around the OS and not the interaction between the new arrays themselves or the older arrays. It's really the operating system itself, which is about 10 million lines of code, and that's where we struggled to really get customer confidence because we are going into these mission critical applications that basically they run the business on, whether it be inventory and retailer, billing, teleco or cable companies those kind of things.
Those are the actual wining and they are coming off of ZMAX, from EMC that have 69's Architecture. So we build the 69 Architecture and it just taken that time to get it hardened and confidence in the customer that they can build the business line.
Nehal Chokshi
Maybe as a frame of reference, what's the incremental million lines of code that you had to implement to introduce the new functionalities that you are going to be introducing next week?
Kevin DeNuccio
Yes, so I think - I don’t have the count of that. The new functionality in it is really all around security and encryption, so that's really the big pieces of code and been added to it. I don’t really have a count of what that was in terms of how much lines of codes have been added, but the rest of the hardening has been really more rearchitecting how the software interacts with each piece of the functionality, but not necessarily more lines of codes, it's cleaning up the architecture so that the interaction was more solid between all of the functionality they have in the OS.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay, great. We can move on to another topic gross margin. So there is a 2.9 million provision for excess and obsolete inventory, is it fair that there was a distribution between some that was excess and some that was obsolete or are they absolutely intertwined?
Cory Sindelar
It's mostly excess. So a portion of that is fully related systems and some of its component parts, but it's not obsolescence and so much as it is excess quantities.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay. And then I think your inventory ticked down less Q-over-Q than the provision that was taken, so I assume that the provision did hit the balance sheet and therefore this does imply that you guys brought in new inventory, is that correct?
Cory Sindelar
Of the provision approximately $2 million of that hit the inventory balance and the other part went into accrued liabilities for component parts that we haven't received in yet.
Nehal Chokshi
I see, okay, all right. So, you didn’t taken any new inventory then basically correct?
Cory Sindelar
Correct.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay, good. And all right - and then that depreciation about $2 million of that, does any of that get record into product COGS.
Cory Sindelar
No, the majority of that would be in R&D.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay. So then it seems like the - it is a real apples-to-apples here that product gross margin did tick down from 25% to 13%. Can you talk about why that was then?
Cory Sindelar
Yes I think if you take a look at kind of the overall product revenue relative to prior quarters, the COGS is going to be a larger percentage of that cost of goods sold and the second thing is obviously pricing in the quarter probably more aggressive as we were trying to pool in as much revenue as possible to close out the quarter.
Nehal Chokshi
Okay. My final question is GlobalLogic deal. Does GlobalLogic retain any IP rights for the development?
Kevin DeNuccio
No.
Nehal Chokshi
Excellent. Thank you.
Operator
And at this time there are no further questions.
Kevin DeNuccio
Well operator then let's go ahead and conclude the call for today. Thank you everybody for joining us.

Operator
Thank you for your participation. This concludes today's conference call. You may now disconnect.
